  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(14) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Besides that which chapmen and merchants brought.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The Hebrew is difficult, and probably corrupt. Literally it seems to run, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "besides the men of the itinerants",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (a strange phrase), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and that which the merchants were bringing;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or, perhaps, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "apart from the men of the itinerants and the merchants bringing.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The last word may be a clerical error, as it occurs again directly. The conjecture of Thenius on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 10:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " seems to be borne out by the ancient Versions. He would read instead of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "’anshê ha-tārîm,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " “men of the travellers,” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "‘onshê ha-r’dûyîm, “fines",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or tributes ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "of the subjects.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Syriac of Chronicles has “tributes of the cities.” Perhaps, therefore, the true original reading was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "‘onshê he‘arîm.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Vulg. renders “envoys of divers peoples;” but the LXX., “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "men of the subjected",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (states).”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For the second half of the phrase Kings has, “and the merchandise of the pedlars.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The kings of Arabia.—Kings, “the kings of the mixed tribes;” that is, the Bêdâwîs, bordering on and mingling with Israel. (Comp. Exodus 12:38.) The difference depends on the vowel pointing only. (Comp. Jeremiah 25:24, where both words occur; and Ezekiel 30:5.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The kings of Arabia.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Kings, “the kings of the mixed tribes;” that is, the ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Bêdâwîs,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " bordering on and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "mingling",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " with Israel. (Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Exodus 12:38",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) The difference depends on the vowel pointing only. (Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jeremiah 25:24",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", where both words occur; and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Ezekiel 30:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Governors.—Pachôth, i.e., pashas. Thenius is wrong in supposing this word to be a token of the “later composition of the section.” (See Note on 2Kings 18:24.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Governors.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Pachôth,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " i.e., pashas. Thenius is wrong in supposing this word to be a token of the “later composition of the section.” (See Note on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Kings 18:24",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Brought.—Were bringing = used to bring. (Comp. 2Chronicles 9:23-24.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Brought.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Were bringing =",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " used to bring. (Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 9:23-24",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
